{"term":"1957","caseName":"Moore v. Michigan","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1957/42","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - October 15, 1957","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13424","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 42, Willie B. Moore, Petitioner, versus State of Michigan.","start":0,"stop":23.541,"duration":23.54},{"text":"Mr. Culver.","start":23.541,"stop":24.698,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please.","start":24.698,"stop":26.595,"duration":1.9},{"text":"This is the case of Willie B. Moore who was sentenced on October 29th, 1938 to life imprisonment in the County of Kalamazoo, Michigan and the sentence was on -- after a plea of guilty to a charge of murder of a lady named Josie Zeedyke.","start":26.595,"stop":45.035,"duration":18.44},{"text":"Mr. Moore, in the 1940s, filed his own papers with the Circuit Court for the County of Kalamazoo.","start":45.035,"stop":54.751,"duration":9.72},{"text":"Sometime later, he was represented in escort in three separate hearings on a delayed motion for a new trial.","start":54.751,"stop":62.657,"duration":7.91},{"text":"After that, Mr. Moore was out of money.His father is a blind man.","start":62.657,"stop":68.958,"duration":6.3},{"text":"His mother is sick.","start":68.958,"stop":71.104,"duration":2.15},{"text":"The Circuit Court appointed me as the attorney for Mr. Moore to attempt the perfected field with the Supreme Court of the State of Michigan.","start":71.104,"stop":79.718,"duration":8.61},{"text":"Subsequently, the Supreme Court denied -- the delayed motion denied the -- granted the appeal but denied the delayed motion for the new trial in a 5-to-3 decision.","start":79.718,"stop":90.706,"duration":10.99},{"text":"And subsequently, this Court has appointed me to represent him at this time.","start":90.706,"stop":97.211,"duration":6.5},{"text":"Now, in arguing this case and looking into this case, we have one barrier which is difficult to overcome.","start":97.211,"stop":107.735,"duration":10.52},{"text":"That is before the De Meerleer case in our Circuit in Kalamazoo.","start":107.735,"stop":112.05,"duration":4.31},{"text":"There was no court reporter of any of the questioning or of any of the procedure that went on at the time of the -- what we call the arraignment, in finding out whether the man needed counsel, whether he could afford counsel.","start":112.05,"stop":126.67,"duration":14.62},{"text":"And I think that's been -- I haven't found that that is in question by the Court at any time but I wish it's pointed out to the Court since I submit that that makes the rate of the problem as to equality of the evidence which is brought before this Court.","start":126.67,"stop":144.374,"duration":17.7},{"text":"The evidence as to what happened at the arraignment is simply the testimony of two or three or four casual witnesses and Mr. (Inaudible) the lawyer who just happened to be in the court and Mr. Zeedyke, son of the murdered lady.","start":144.374,"stop":160.239,"duration":15.87},{"text":"And it raises a difficult problem on appeal which would never have occurred at this time.","start":160.239,"stop":164.585,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this a common thing and --","start":164.585,"stop":166.635,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"It's no longer --","start":166.635,"stop":167.499,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":167.499,"stop":168.183,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"It's no longer the rule in --","start":168.183,"stop":170.376,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"One of the terms of this case is that there was nothing peculiar about the way this case (Voice Overlap) --","start":170.376,"stop":173.321,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"There was nothing peculiar about this particular one.","start":173.321,"stop":176.021,"duration":2.7},{"text":"However --","start":176.021,"stop":176.064,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what was -- in this -- what is matter of record Mr. Culver?","start":176.064,"stop":181.104,"duration":5.04}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"As far as the arraignment is concerned, it just says arraignment and plea.","start":181.104,"stop":185.943,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought the -- there were some remarks of the judge.","start":185.943,"stop":188.625,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"And subsequently, in the term -- after the plea, in the determination of the decree where there was first, second, third manslaughter there were questions of the doctor who have attended to --","start":188.625,"stop":199.696,"duration":11.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, not the doctor but the judge himself has presumptions that he put --","start":199.696,"stop":204.2,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":204.2,"stop":204.32,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that was contemporaneous (Voice Overlap) --","start":204.32,"stop":205.34,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"There are subsequent statements by the judge that he was (Voice Overlap) --","start":205.34,"stop":208.946,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How come -- that's what I want to know.","start":208.946,"stop":210.442,"duration":1.5},{"text":"Wasn't it -- wasn't it contemporaneous?","start":210.442,"stop":212.721,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"It was.","start":212.721,"stop":213.472,"duration":0.75},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":213.472,"stop":214.884,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not --","start":214.884,"stop":215.097,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Subsequent to the plea.","start":215.097,"stop":216.591,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":216.591,"stop":216.939,"duration":0.35},{"text":"What else -- that's the same or whatever it was.","start":216.939,"stop":218.576,"duration":1.64},{"text":"The next evidence whatever it is?","start":218.576,"stop":220.261,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":220.261,"stop":220.825,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not years after reconstruction, wasn't it?","start":220.825,"stop":223.096,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":223.096,"stop":224.198,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That was a matter of record, was it not?","start":224.198,"stop":225.655,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"That was -- in the -- it -- in that statement which is the standard form of -- we followed in our -- we followed in our County.","start":225.655,"stop":234.386,"duration":8.73},{"text":"However, subsequent evidence --","start":234.386,"stop":235.336,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you didn't have it in -- in the -- what do you call it?","start":235.336,"stop":238.903,"duration":3.57}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What's that?","start":238.903,"stop":239.329,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"De Meerleer case (Inaudible)","start":239.329,"stop":240.912,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"De Meerleer.","start":240.912,"stop":241.913,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"De Meerleer.","start":241.913,"stop":242.448,"duration":0.53},{"text":"We didn't have that there.","start":242.448,"stop":243.063,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe so.","start":243.063,"stop":245.175,"duration":2.11},{"text":"Now --","start":245.175,"stop":245.56,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What did he say?","start":245.56,"stop":246.871,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"He said that he had satisfied himself that the plea was freely and voluntarily made.","start":246.871,"stop":253.018,"duration":6.15},{"text":"And he also discussed the fact that this man has voluntarily or had -- had confessed the crime, this horrible crime which had been --","start":253.018,"stop":264.919,"duration":11.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Why don't -- would you take two minutes to read it because --","start":264.919,"stop":268.11,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":268.11,"stop":268.99,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I think there's some importance (Inaudible)","start":268.99,"stop":275.901,"duration":6.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":275.901,"stop":277.468,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":277.468,"stop":277.906,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":277.906,"stop":279.967,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"After the plea and the -- at the time of defense.","start":279.967,"stop":284.573,"duration":4.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it seem Mr. Culver when I get (Inaudible), is there some special proceedings (Inaudible) following a plea in homicide cases?","start":284.573,"stop":293.83,"duration":9.26}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":293.83,"stop":294.602,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And that is a proceeding with special (Inaudible)","start":294.602,"stop":299.875,"duration":5.27}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":299.875,"stop":300.76,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And in addition to that, the fact was for the judge to make a statement?","start":300.76,"stop":304.151,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":304.151,"stop":305.015,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what happened (Inaudible) of the record?","start":305.015,"stop":310.551,"duration":5.54}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, the judge said, \"In my private interview with respondent, I assured him that he must not plead guilty unless he really is guilty; that he was not required to plead guilty; that he could have a trial by jury if he desired it.","start":310.551,"stop":323.759,"duration":13.21},{"text":"He assured me freely and voluntarily that he is guilty and that his one desire is to have it all over, to get to the institution to which he is to be committed, and to be under observation and to be examined.”","start":323.759,"stop":335.146,"duration":11.39},{"text":"That's on page 15 of the transcript of records.","start":335.146,"stop":338.338,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What is -- what's the record of the witness who was identified as the father of Brown -- of Moore, I beg your pardon, who was identified as a father of Moore and he urged Moore not to plead or indicated at all.","start":338.338,"stop":356.016,"duration":17.68}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":356.016,"stop":356.634,"duration":0.62},{"text":"There was --","start":356.634,"stop":357.048,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that -- was that the record of that made at that time?","start":357.048,"stop":361.247,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"That, if -- if I understand, Mr. Justice, correctly, that was a record attempt to get into the record of prior conviction of Mr. Moore.","start":361.247,"stop":373.157,"duration":11.91},{"text":"Mr. Moore's father was not involved here at all.","start":373.157,"stop":376.556,"duration":3.4},{"text":"He was --","start":376.556,"stop":376.64,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I know.","start":376.64,"stop":377.167,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"He lost contact of his parents at all.","start":377.167,"stop":379.219,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I thought when this -- when -- was it Judge Weimer who --","start":379.219,"stop":382.496,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Judge Weimer.","start":382.496,"stop":383.184,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- who did this that before he sentenced him that when he was pleading guilty, there was a voice, spectator in the court who was after identified as the father.","start":383.184,"stop":396.143,"duration":12.96},{"text":"Did I get it all wrong?","start":396.143,"stop":397.025,"duration":0.88},{"text":"Is this imagining under my part?","start":397.025,"stop":398.802,"duration":1.78},{"text":"It must be.","start":398.802,"stop":400.865,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that the record shows that the only time he did contact his parents was the half hour after he was sentenced and before he went to Jackson Prison.","start":400.865,"stop":413.311,"duration":12.45},{"text":"But there's no -- he didn't at any time speak with his parents.","start":413.311,"stop":417.045,"duration":3.73},{"text":"They may have been in the courtroom.","start":417.045,"stop":419.797,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't want to waste your time.","start":419.797,"stop":421.302,"duration":1.5},{"text":"I'll find it (Inaudible)","start":421.302,"stop":424.414,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"In attempting to break this down in a nice category to defies that sort of thing but we think that substantially it shows -- the record shows that the plea of guilty was gained by duress and coercion and that there was a failure to provide counsel in this particular case which should have been provided.","start":424.414,"stop":443.204,"duration":18.79},{"text":"And what shows the duress and coercion, first all, Mr. Moore at the time of -- of his plea, was 17 years old.","start":443.204,"stop":451.08,"duration":7.88},{"text":"He was a colored man.","start":451.08,"stop":452.733,"duration":1.65},{"text":"He's been in Michigan about 10 years.","start":452.733,"stop":455.183,"duration":2.45},{"text":"He had a seventh-grade education.","start":455.183,"stop":457.885,"duration":2.7},{"text":"He was -- and this is undisputed.","start":457.885,"stop":460.181,"duration":2.3},{"text":"He was arrested on the afternoon of October 26, Wednesday afternoon.","start":460.181,"stop":464.997,"duration":4.82},{"text":"He was questioned until about 2 to 3 o'clock the next morning.","start":464.997,"stop":468.72,"duration":3.72},{"text":"Questioned on the next day until about 8 or 9 at night, he was questioned until approximately 11 at night.","start":468.72,"stop":475.865,"duration":7.14},{"text":"He was questioned the next day and questioned there would be Friday until the afternoon.","start":475.865,"stop":480.418,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any dispute about the length of the questioning?","start":480.418,"stop":483.011,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"None, Your Honor.","start":483.011,"stop":483.527,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"None.","start":483.527,"stop":484.675,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, in my brief I've stated that under McNabb, this might -- this would come under the -- the Due Process Clause on the limitation of federal rights.","start":484.675,"stop":494.809,"duration":10.13},{"text":"And I know that the Court has not so held.","start":494.809,"stop":497.227,"duration":2.42},{"text":"But I submit that in this particular case, in view of the other facts involved that it -- it does raise along with the other facts, a due process problem, and that is questioning the arraignment that is the original examination by Mr. Moore occurred after he had been questioned for approximately three days and our statute provides that most statutes do that you take the man before the nearest convenient examining magistrate as soon as you can do it.","start":497.227,"stop":524.804,"duration":27.58},{"text":"In this case, he was not taken before the magistrate.And he was a young man and fully educated and a literate.","start":524.804,"stop":533.351,"duration":8.55},{"text":"Now, what happened during this questioning?","start":533.351,"stop":538.231,"duration":4.88},{"text":"Here it seems to me is the important point.","start":538.231,"stop":542.046,"duration":3.82},{"text":"There is on the record the statement by the judge that he was satisfied that the plea was freely and involuntarily made and we don't question that the judge said that.","start":542.046,"stop":549.613,"duration":7.57},{"text":"But at that time, he didn't know what had happened.","start":549.613,"stop":552.541,"duration":2.93},{"text":"And we didn't know what had happened until at 1950 or 1951 when Sheriff Struble who was the sheriff at the time of Willie Moore's arraignment and arrest, when Sheriff Struble testified before the -- the Circuit Court.","start":552.541,"stop":568.615,"duration":16.07},{"text":"And when he was asked what did he say to Mr. Moore, to the 17-year-old fellow, he said, “It is my duty, and it is up to me to protect you, to use every effort at my command to protect you, but, I says, “the tension is high out there and I am just telling you what could happen if it was started by someone.”","start":568.615,"stop":586.813,"duration":18.2},{"text":"I don't know the language I used.”","start":586.813,"stop":589.114,"duration":2.3},{"text":"Then he goes on to say, “I don't know as I come out and said at any time for him to plead one way or another, but what I was putting over to him was the fact that if you are guilty and will be sent away, you might better be getting away before trouble, because I had had information that there were certain colored fellows, a group of them, that was going to interfere with me, and also that there was a bunch of Holland fellows going to meet me when I go to Jackson, they would meet me there at Galesburg there, and, therefore, when he was sentenced, I avoided the main route and went way through by Gull Lake and across over in the hills.”","start":589.114,"stop":622.445,"duration":33.33},{"text":"Now what you may say yourself well, that wouldn't seem to affect me.","start":622.445,"stop":629.282,"duration":6.84},{"text":"I wouldn't plead guilty to a crime just because the sheriff said that.","start":629.282,"stop":633.945,"duration":4.66},{"text":"But we contend that the effect on Mr. Moore was just as he said.","start":633.945,"stop":639.597,"duration":5.65},{"text":"“After the man tell me he couldn't protect me then there was nothing -- then there wasn't nothing I could do.","start":639.597,"stop":646.038,"duration":6.44},{"text":"I was mostly scared than anything else.”","start":646.038,"stop":649.133,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That testimony was before the Circuit Judge --","start":649.133,"stop":652.838,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":652.838,"stop":653.872,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and (Voice Overlap) --","start":653.872,"stop":654.705,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"-- before Judge -- Judge Sweet on a delayed motion.","start":654.705,"stop":659.064,"duration":4.36}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"This was 11 and a half years after dealing with the result.","start":659.064,"stop":663,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":663,"stop":664.26,"duration":1.26},{"text":"Now, the delay was not the delay and the failure to have a record was not the failure of Mr. Moore.","start":664.26,"stop":671.518,"duration":7.26},{"text":"He was imprisoned and as I've indicated to you to have counsel, he had to have counsel appointed by the Circuit Court of County Kalamazoo.","start":671.518,"stop":679.928,"duration":8.41},{"text":"And during the time of his incarceration in this questioning, he was not allowed to permit his relatives or his friends and he did not in fact permit them or -- or contact them.","start":679.928,"stop":691.44,"duration":11.51},{"text":"And that also is undisputed.","start":691.44,"stop":693.964,"duration":2.52},{"text":"There is no question about that.","start":693.964,"stop":696.341,"duration":2.38},{"text":"And further, he was without counsel.","start":696.341,"stop":699.697,"duration":3.36},{"text":"And there is some evidence in this hearing that counsel was mentioned to him but it's undisputed of course that he was without the benefit of counsel.","start":699.697,"stop":708.779,"duration":9.08},{"text":"He was in an isolated cell.","start":708.779,"stop":712.643,"duration":3.86},{"text":"Its -- I see now in the brief first which was furnished to me by the people that they have pictures of the -- the prison showing that you couldn't get up, this particular spot.","start":712.643,"stop":725.461,"duration":12.82},{"text":"However, it's submitted that Mr. Moore has indicated the people that were there were brought up as visitors and that they pounded on the cell, on his cell that evening and they -- they threatened him and they shouted.","start":725.461,"stop":738.343,"duration":12.88},{"text":"And in particular, one said, “Well, let's get him now and I'll get it over with.”","start":738.343,"stop":746.364,"duration":8.02},{"text":"And that then is when this hammering started on the door up there.","start":746.364,"stop":750.429,"duration":4.06},{"text":"And I submit that that was occurring on until the fear in Mr. Moore from the time -- right onto to the time on Saturday morning when -- when he pleaded guilty and he was sent to prison.","start":750.429,"stop":764.737,"duration":14.31},{"text":"And further undisputed on the record, I submit are the -- that the prosecutor and members of the police promised him a shorter sentence if he should plead guilty.","start":764.737,"stop":775.503,"duration":10.77},{"text":"Now, next, and I think running into the same thing is and the same facts are applicable was the fact the counsel was not appointed.","start":775.503,"stop":783.453,"duration":7.95},{"text":"This is as capital offenses as -- as we have in Michigan.","start":783.453,"stop":786.515,"duration":3.06},{"text":"Obviously, we don't have a death sentence but we do have this murder in the first degree which is mandatory life and the man goes to prison for life, forever, there is no parole, no pardon, perhaps there's pardon but there's no parole.","start":786.515,"stop":802.807,"duration":16.29},{"text":"So this is a serious case.","start":802.807,"stop":804.33,"duration":1.52},{"text":"This is as serious as you can get.","start":804.33,"stop":806.598,"duration":2.27},{"text":"He was 17 years old.","start":806.598,"stop":808.257,"duration":1.66},{"text":"He had a seventh-grade education.","start":808.257,"stop":810.604,"duration":2.35},{"text":"There's a lot of evidence, a lot of testimony in the record that try to show that he was an experienced criminal and where -- where the evidence came that he had four or five difficulties with the -- with the police, I don't know.","start":810.604,"stop":825.616,"duration":15.01},{"text":"However, if -- if that's true, if that's what he told the judge, then they -- they were juvenile offenses and they were not record offenses.","start":825.616,"stop":834.937,"duration":9.32},{"text":"And the only offense which is shown in the record is the offense some two weeks before in Grand Rapids when he pleaded guilty to unlawfully driving away a car.","start":834.937,"stop":844.325,"duration":9.39},{"text":"And the evidence shows in that case that the contact between the Police Officer, Mr. Cole and -- was between him and (Inaudible) said he was the father of Willie Moore he was mixed up by that.","start":844.325,"stop":856.901,"duration":12.58},{"text":"It was between him and the mother and we just asked the mother, “Do you think you ought to have a lawyer for him?”","start":856.901,"stop":862.761,"duration":5.86},{"text":"And -- and apparently she said, “No.”","start":862.761,"stop":865.289,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there anything that indicates the reasons for the 10-year delay and in making this motion showing up this writ?","start":865.289,"stop":879.873,"duration":14.58}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't -- I don't believe so except for the fact that the appointment by the Court of -- of counsel, the fact that the boy did -- didn't have any money.","start":879.873,"stop":889.457,"duration":9.58},{"text":"He had no way of -- of having counsel, paying for counsel.","start":889.457,"stop":896.25,"duration":6.79},{"text":"And that would be the only reason.However, as the Court has decided in other cases a mere delay in bringing this type of thing is -- is not an important matter.","start":896.25,"stop":908.432,"duration":12.18},{"text":"And this man, as I say, his -- his father is blind, his mother is sick, he just didn't have money to bring.","start":908.432,"stop":917.193,"duration":8.76},{"text":"And I would like to -- to say -- go on to one this counsel question.","start":917.193,"stop":924.997,"duration":7.8},{"text":"First of all, is that the -- the people say, “Well, this isn't a complicated charge.","start":924.997,"stop":929.84,"duration":4.84},{"text":"Well, the man -- the man was charged with murder.”","start":929.84,"stop":932.228,"duration":2.39},{"text":"In Michigan, we have first degree murder, second degree murder, manslaughter, you can't get anymore -- you can't use one word and mean any more things than you can with that particular word.","start":932.228,"stop":942.233,"duration":10},{"text":"And I would like to call the Court's attention to the fact that this was a horrible crime.","start":942.233,"stop":947.424,"duration":5.19},{"text":"This was a rape of a 68-year-old woman, there was stabbing, there was murder, and I submit that in -- if this man was brought before our Circuit Court at this time, with facts of that type, a counsel would be appointed for him.","start":947.424,"stop":961.659,"duration":14.24},{"text":"And I would like also to --","start":961.659,"stop":965.851,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Your statute now required that, doesn't it Mr. Culver?","start":965.851,"stop":968.265,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes, sir.","start":968.265,"stop":969.832,"duration":1.57},{"text":"And subsequent to the De Meerleer case, our court rules immediately ordered that the man be notified.","start":969.832,"stop":976,"duration":6.17},{"text":"And our Circuit Judge has a regular form which he uses which informs the man, he reads it often and says “You're entitled to counsel,” and all those various things.","start":976,"stop":985.064,"duration":9.06},{"text":"All of those things have been changed since that time.","start":985.064,"stop":988.019,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Culver, this delayed motion for new trial, is that the style of some recognized form of motion or was it a post conviction proceeding at that time?","start":988.019,"stop":996.808,"duration":8.79}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":996.808,"stop":997.579,"duration":0.77},{"text":"Under our statutes and our rules, you -- your period for appeal can be -- or -- for a motion for a new trial can be extended if you show the court that there are certain reasons why it wasn't done and -- and implicit in the granting of this delayed motion by our Circuit Judge is the fact that there were reasons.","start":997.579,"stop":1019.617,"duration":22.04}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How long is that procedure been operating?","start":1019.617,"stop":1021.472,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"It's been operative at least 10 years.","start":1021.472,"stop":1026.423,"duration":4.95},{"text":"It's been operative as far as the De Meerleer case was concerned and the Quicksall case, all of which cases were decided by this Court.","start":1026.423,"stop":1032.172,"duration":5.75}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did they come operative after Moore was sentenced?","start":1032.172,"stop":1037.565,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe so.","start":1037.565,"stop":1038.905,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You think it was in effect at the time he was sentenced?","start":1038.905,"stop":1040.486,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe it was.","start":1040.486,"stop":1041.996,"duration":1.51},{"text":"I -- I would like to --","start":1041.996,"stop":1042.573,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Culver, before you get to the other phase, what is the record show about a lesser sentence if he pleaded?","start":1042.573,"stop":1050.946,"duration":8.37},{"text":"You made mention on that a moment ago.","start":1050.946,"stop":1053.076,"duration":2.13},{"text":"Is there -- is that a substantial point in the case?","start":1053.076,"stop":1056.901,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"That if he --","start":1056.901,"stop":1057.935,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"He pled guilty he will get a lesser sentence?","start":1057.935,"stop":1061.268,"duration":3.33},{"text":"Did he so testify?","start":1061.268,"stop":1062.339,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"He so testified.","start":1062.339,"stop":1063.543,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Was it controverted?","start":1063.543,"stop":1064.695,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"It was not controverted.","start":1064.695,"stop":1066.53,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he name the man who told him that?","start":1066.53,"stop":1068.618,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, he said that the Chief of Police, Mr. Chapman, promised him a lesser sentence.","start":1068.618,"stop":1073.794,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Was Mr. Chapman living in available to the -- to the people at the time the hearing --","start":1073.794,"stop":1081.4,"duration":7.61}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chapman, all I know, is from what Mr. Sykes who was the prosecutor at the time said Mr. Chapman was a judge and that was living in Florida at the time and --","start":1081.4,"stop":1092.158,"duration":10.76}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 35 of the record.","start":1092.158,"stop":1094.869,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"I may -- I may have Struble and Chapman mixed up but as I recall Mr. Sykes, who adjourned the hearing so that he could get Mr. Chapman's testimony.","start":1094.869,"stop":1102.507,"duration":7.64},{"text":"And it was not brought --","start":1102.507,"stop":1104.676,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"He did not brought.","start":1104.676,"stop":1105.5,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"He was -- he didn't testify.","start":1105.5,"stop":1106.918,"duration":1.42},{"text":"Mr. Chapman didn't.","start":1106.918,"stop":1108.442,"duration":1.52},{"text":"I would like to point out that the Michigan Supreme Court, in this position, if you read the decision, you'll see the first three questions involved.","start":1108.442,"stop":1119.415,"duration":10.97},{"text":"I -- I pray that this Court does not decide the case on those -- on that basis.","start":1119.415,"stop":1123.749,"duration":4.33},{"text":"First is, they decided on whether or not this man was guilty or innocent.","start":1123.749,"stop":1129.218,"duration":5.47},{"text":"I was appointed by the Court not to determine a guilt or innocence of this man and this Court, I'm sure, is well aware that that's not the question here.","start":1129.218,"stop":1137.631,"duration":8.41},{"text":"The question is where -- was he granted his constitutional rights.","start":1137.631,"stop":1141.598,"duration":3.97},{"text":"The second thing which the Supreme Court said is that it's difficult to get evidence to have a trial after 17 years have elapsed.","start":1141.598,"stop":1150.006,"duration":8.41},{"text":"Again, I submit that's not relevant.","start":1150.006,"stop":1153.05,"duration":3.04},{"text":"And then finally, the -- the Court says we're worried about the possible consequences of returning to society, a person likely to increase the public burden of sex crimes.","start":1153.05,"stop":1164.065,"duration":11.02},{"text":"Again, I submit to the Court that that is the reason why this case is here.","start":1164.065,"stop":1168.612,"duration":4.55},{"text":"If this Court is so far away from -- quite a waste away from our tribunal and that is because of the fact that it should not be decided on that.","start":1168.612,"stop":1177.525,"duration":8.91},{"text":"It should be decided not on difficulty of proof or the burden on society but whether or not this man was granted his constitutional rights.","start":1177.525,"stop":1185.77,"duration":8.24},{"text":"And that -- the -- Mr. Shepherd who was a former -- former Solicitor General from Michigan was a little worried about this thing too and his response to our petition, he said it is the testimony of the former Sheriff that troubles somewhat for a word unqualified or if it showed beyond doubt that this officer, that is Sheriff Struble, by threats of my violence so and still the petitioner was here that he was induced to confess and plead guilty.","start":1185.77,"stop":1210.564,"duration":24.79},{"text":"The position of the State might prove untenable.","start":1210.564,"stop":1213.428,"duration":2.86},{"text":"Now, he did not admit error there, he just -- and -- and he wanted this to come before this Court, as I understand it, to see whether it was shown that the threats of my violence, the statements to this man were sufficient.","start":1213.428,"stop":1228.924,"duration":15.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What was that you are reading from, Mr. Culver?","start":1228.924,"stop":1230.433,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the response of the State of Michigan in -- on -- to our application for writ of certiorari to the Supreme Court of the State Michigan and it's filed in the files and records of this case.","start":1230.433,"stop":1244.338,"duration":13.9},{"text":"Again, I -- I wish to thank very much for the opportunity to appear here and to represent Mr. Moore.","start":1244.338,"stop":1253.337,"duration":9}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Torina, Mr. Solicitor General.","start":1253.337,"stop":1260.494,"duration":7.16}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor.","start":1260.494,"stop":1261.321,"duration":0.83},{"text":"May it please the Court, Mr. Justice Warren.","start":1261.321,"stop":1264.333,"duration":3.01},{"text":"I regret to announce that Mr. Shepherd, my predecessor retired this June, after many long years before this Court.","start":1264.333,"stop":1272.787,"duration":8.45},{"text":"He was paying many tributes when he retired.","start":1272.787,"stop":1275.658,"duration":2.87},{"text":"But I think the one that he cherished most was the one that you paid him last year in the Butler case where you expressed your appreciation of his candor before this Court.","start":1275.658,"stop":1286.691,"duration":11.03},{"text":"I hope that when I retire, and I will have earned the same accolade from this Court because I really feel that these quick justice cases are the kind that disturbed everybody.","start":1286.691,"stop":1301.383,"duration":14.69},{"text":"You have a young man here, 17 years old.","start":1301.383,"stop":1305.212,"duration":3.83},{"text":"He pleads guilty to under a very serious crime.","start":1305.212,"stop":1308.519,"duration":3.31},{"text":"He's not represented by an attorney.","start":1308.519,"stop":1310.686,"duration":2.17},{"text":"I started to say without benefit of attorney but that's my view upon waiting.","start":1310.686,"stop":1315.456,"duration":4.77},{"text":"But anyhow, he's not represented by an attorney.","start":1315.456,"stop":1318.232,"duration":2.78},{"text":"And it causes all of us a lot of concern.","start":1318.232,"stop":1321.744,"duration":3.51},{"text":"I was concerned about it when I got the record.","start":1321.744,"stop":1324.936,"duration":3.19},{"text":"And I started very carefully.","start":1324.936,"stop":1326.73,"duration":1.79},{"text":"I even went to Kalamazoo to look at the jail and I included the picture of the jail here for that reason.","start":1326.73,"stop":1332.968,"duration":6.24},{"text":"I wanted you to see what type of jail this man was confined in by the time he entered his plea.","start":1332.968,"stop":1339.806,"duration":6.84},{"text":"And if you will notice, it's a rather massive pile of brick and marble.","start":1339.806,"stop":1345.162,"duration":5.36},{"text":"It was built in 1937 on WPA funds partly and is used as a federal jail also.","start":1345.162,"stop":1353.75,"duration":8.59},{"text":"And the cells, the solitary cell which is referred here is not a solitary cell alone.","start":1353.75,"stop":1360.07,"duration":6.32},{"text":"It's solitary in the sense that it's all to this side but there is a door, an iron door that leads to it.","start":1360.07,"stop":1366.984,"duration":6.91},{"text":"And then there is another door outside that's made of iron.","start":1366.984,"stop":1370.195,"duration":3.21},{"text":"And when I saw this cell, it was brightly lit up, you could see into it and there was an intoxicated man who had been confined there.","start":1370.195,"stop":1378.642,"duration":8.45},{"text":"That's the kind of a cell that is.","start":1378.642,"stop":1380.77,"duration":2.13},{"text":"So when they speak about solitary cell here, they don't -- it doesn't mean solitary in the sense of putting some man down the hole.","start":1380.77,"stop":1388.216,"duration":7.45},{"text":"I also talked with Judge Fox.","start":1388.216,"stop":1390.819,"duration":2.6},{"text":"I want to make sure that when he took the statement from Moore in this case, I want to see what type of a man he was.","start":1390.819,"stop":1399.101,"duration":8.28},{"text":"Well, he's an able and respected judge there in Kalamazoo.","start":1399.101,"stop":1401.723,"duration":2.62},{"text":"He was the assistant prosecutor who took the statement -- the statement here.","start":1401.723,"stop":1405.785,"duration":4.06},{"text":"And I asked him when he took the statement just what he thought on Willie Moore's condition.","start":1405.785,"stop":1410.172,"duration":4.39},{"text":"And he said he thought the plea was free and voluntarily.","start":1410.172,"stop":1412.883,"duration":2.71},{"text":"He had no worries about it.","start":1412.883,"stop":1414.68,"duration":1.8},{"text":"He was still convinced of that.","start":1414.68,"stop":1415.925,"duration":1.24},{"text":"I talked to Mr. (Inaudible) who is still down there and to several other people.","start":1415.925,"stop":1421.714,"duration":5.79},{"text":"Well, after I saw that, I decided that we would oppose this motion and do the best we can here.","start":1421.714,"stop":1427.794,"duration":6.08},{"text":"Now, I'm glad of one thing.","start":1427.794,"stop":1431.008,"duration":3.21},{"text":"We will not have, I hope any more of Willie Moore case in Michigan.","start":1431.008,"stop":1435.336,"duration":4.33},{"text":"We have revised our court rules and our statutes since that time.","start":1435.336,"stop":1440.919,"duration":5.58},{"text":"Under the De Meerleer case within a month later, we revised our proceedings there, our court rules which hand of course substantial in our State.","start":1440.919,"stop":1451.229,"duration":10.31},{"text":"And that provided that when a man pleads guilty or offers to plead guilty, the court before accepting the plea has to advise him of his right to counsel and right to a jury trial.","start":1451.229,"stop":1462.879,"duration":11.65},{"text":"And then if -- if the man advised the court, he is unable to afford counsel then the court will appoint one.","start":1462.879,"stop":1470.151,"duration":7.27},{"text":"We've even gone so far now and I think further in most States, we've tried to find the suggestions made by this Court.","start":1470.151,"stop":1477.451,"duration":7.3},{"text":"We allow a man to request an attorney at a preliminary examination now.","start":1477.451,"stop":1483.548,"duration":6.1},{"text":"I know that statute was just passed three months ago.","start":1483.548,"stop":1485.843,"duration":2.3},{"text":"I've had a little trouble interpreting who the presiding judge would appoint.","start":1485.843,"stop":1489.683,"duration":3.84},{"text":"I have to interpret that but there is no question now if a man comes at a preliminary examination in our State and request an attorney it will -- he will be appointed one.","start":1489.683,"stop":1499.441,"duration":9.76},{"text":"So we will not handle that State.","start":1499.441,"stop":1500.933,"duration":1.49},{"text":"We -- our State does not believe in depriving anybody of his rights.","start":1500.933,"stop":1504.782,"duration":3.85},{"text":"I've been through the -- this procedure under Rule of 35-A many times in my job as an assistant prosecutor in Wayne County.","start":1504.782,"stop":1514.124,"duration":9.34},{"text":"I know the exact procedure when the man said he wants to plead guilty, the judge stops the proceeding and says, \"Do you want an attorney to represent you?\"","start":1514.124,"stop":1522.215,"duration":8.09},{"text":"And if he said, \"Yes.\"","start":1522.215,"stop":1523.15,"duration":0.94},{"text":"And he appoints an attorney for him.","start":1523.15,"stop":1525.021,"duration":1.87},{"text":"And the record is made of a whole proceeding.","start":1525.021,"stop":1526.714,"duration":1.69},{"text":"If a man pleads guilty, he's asked to plead guilty freely and voluntarily, he's asked if he's guilty.","start":1526.714,"stop":1533.246,"duration":6.53},{"text":"He's pleading guilty because he is guilty.","start":1533.246,"stop":1535.391,"duration":2.14},{"text":"He's asked of any threats or violence has been used on him.","start":1535.391,"stop":1538.985,"duration":3.59},{"text":"So we don't have that situation anymore.","start":1538.985,"stop":1541.164,"duration":2.18},{"text":"Thank the Lord.","start":1541.164,"stop":1542.362,"duration":1.2},{"text":"And I hope we'll never have another one like this one.","start":1542.362,"stop":1544.709,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll --","start":1544.709,"stop":1544.922,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"But --","start":1544.922,"stop":1545.396,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- we'll recess now.","start":1545.396,"stop":1546.222,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, Your Honor.","start":1546.222,"stop":1546.987,"duration":0.77},{"text":"Tomorrow morning.","start":1546.987,"stop":1548.243,"duration":1.26},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1548.243,"stop":1553.368,"duration":5.13}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - October 16, 1957","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13474","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 42, Willie B. Moore versus State of Michigan.","start":0,"stop":6.256,"duration":6.26},{"text":"Mr. Solicitor General, you may continue.","start":6.256,"stop":9.49,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":9.49,"stop":14.041,"duration":4.55},{"text":"Yesterday, when the adjournment is called up, I was discussing the question of procedure in Michigan involved in this case.","start":14.041,"stop":22.639,"duration":8.6},{"text":"I think I'll continue on because I think that the proceedings that were involved in this case are very important to its determination.","start":22.639,"stop":31.672,"duration":9.03},{"text":"Now, I would like to profess my argument by pointing out that these proceedings have been before this Court prior to this time.","start":31.672,"stop":39.311,"duration":7.64},{"text":"They were considered in the Quicksall versus Michigan case which Mr. Justice Frankfurter wrote the opinion on and approved or I would like to review them again.","start":39.311,"stop":50.834,"duration":11.52},{"text":"Now, Willie B. Moore was arraigned on information.","start":50.834,"stop":55.031,"duration":4.2},{"text":"It wasn't a complicated information.","start":55.031,"stop":57.647,"duration":2.62},{"text":"It was count in simple language that run in substance as follows.","start":57.647,"stop":62.093,"duration":4.45},{"text":"Now, Willie B. Moore heretofore to wit on or about the 26th day of October 1938 at the City of Kalamazoo in the County of Kalamazoo aforesaid murdered Josie Zeedyke.","start":62.093,"stop":77.607,"duration":15.51},{"text":"And then after that the Court -- the Court reporter's transcript shows that the accused was arraigned and pleaded guilty in the official general entry which appears here.","start":77.607,"stop":88.978,"duration":11.37},{"text":"Now, this arraignment was on the 29th day of October in 1938, and the general entry under our law raised the strong presumptions and it discloses that following the plea -- but before imposing sentence, the trial judge took two important procedural steps in accordance with our state law.","start":88.978,"stop":110.096,"duration":21.12},{"text":"Now, I think I mentioned yesterday that at the time this case was tried, Rule 35-A didn't exist.","start":110.096,"stop":118.996,"duration":8.9},{"text":"We did have a statute which still exist, which provided that on the plea of guilty, the judge was to discover from the witness whether he pleaded guilty voluntarily or not.","start":118.996,"stop":131.684,"duration":12.69},{"text":"There wasn't any procedure outlined by which that discovery was to be made and several has been used throughout the state and approved by our court.","start":131.684,"stop":144.378,"duration":12.69},{"text":"On this case, according to a witness, the colloquy took place between Willie B. Moore and the judge for about 15 minutes.","start":144.378,"stop":152.318,"duration":7.94},{"text":"This witness was running sure who was an attorney spectator in the court at the time this arraignment took place, He said it was about 9 o'clock in the morning.","start":152.318,"stop":161.776,"duration":9.46},{"text":"Well anyhow, after this colloquy, the judge took Willie Moore into his chambers and Willie Moore says that at the time he was accompanied by Sheriff Rubel (ph).","start":161.776,"stop":174.466,"duration":12.69},{"text":"However, Rubel (ph) denied that he went into the chambers with the judge and the judge then, according to this record, which has been put on file, he made a statement of the proceedings first.","start":174.466,"stop":187.435,"duration":12.97},{"text":"Now he put on file.","start":187.435,"stop":189.066,"duration":1.63},{"text":"He discussed with Willie B. Moore his -- his education, his background and then he says Willie Moore gave him all the details of the crime.","start":189.066,"stop":198.259,"duration":9.19},{"text":"And when he came out, he put that on the record.","start":198.259,"stop":201.254,"duration":3},{"text":"Had the description of the crime as given by Willie Moore and then he ended up with this statement that appears on page 15 of the record.","start":201.254,"stop":212.092,"duration":10.84},{"text":"“In my private interview with respondent, I assured him that he must not plead guilty unless he really is guilty, that he was not required to plead guilty, that he could have a trial by jury if he desired it.","start":212.092,"stop":228.039,"duration":15.95},{"text":"He assured me freely and voluntarily that he is guilty and that his one desire is to have it all over to get to the institution to which he is committed and to be under observation and to be examined.","start":228.039,"stop":240.604,"duration":12.57},{"text":"Now, that was put on the day of the arraignment.","start":240.604,"stop":243.007,"duration":2.4},{"text":"That was put on record and appeared in the official Court records.","start":243.007,"stop":247.91,"duration":4.9},{"text":"That was the statement he made.","start":247.91,"stop":249.812,"duration":1.9},{"text":"Following that, the judge then took a second statutory statement.","start":249.812,"stop":254.23,"duration":4.42},{"text":"Our statute still requires that upon a plea of guilty in the case of murder, the judge has to put witnesses on the stand to determine the degree of guilt.","start":254.23,"stop":264.281,"duration":10.05},{"text":"If that isn't done, our Court has -- and that hasn't been done in a couple of case and each time our Court has avoided this -- the sentence.","start":264.281,"stop":272.431,"duration":8.15},{"text":"Well, the judge then had I think three -- three witnesses were put on the stand.","start":272.431,"stop":280.303,"duration":7.87},{"text":"One was the daughter of the deceased or the -- of the murdered woman, (Inaudible) Zeedyke and she testified that she saw Willie Moore come to the house on the day he asked her if they had any work to do.","start":280.303,"stop":292.754,"duration":12.45},{"text":"She knew him.","start":292.754,"stop":293.313,"duration":0.56},{"text":"She had met him previously to this time because Willie Moore had worked for her brother.","start":293.313,"stop":298.02,"duration":4.71},{"text":"And after that, she said she saw him (Inaudible) she found her mother.","start":298.02,"stop":302.203,"duration":4.18},{"text":"Another witness was a policeman who is called to the scene of the murder and he testified as to the condition of the woman and then the coroner testified.","start":302.203,"stop":313.085,"duration":10.88},{"text":"The coroner or the doctor as to the condition of the woman, what caused her death and so on and while I think of -- there was a police.","start":313.085,"stop":320.558,"duration":7.47},{"text":"I -- I don't recall exactly.","start":320.558,"stop":322.096,"duration":1.54},{"text":"It's in the transcript.","start":322.096,"stop":323.081,"duration":0.99},{"text":"There are three or four witnesses.","start":323.081,"stop":323.252,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Solicitor, what -- was that the testimony of those witnesses taken before the private interview?","start":323.252,"stop":330.106,"duration":6.85}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't believe so, Your Honor.","start":330.106,"stop":331.268,"duration":1.16},{"text":"It was taken after.","start":331.268,"stop":332.744,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it appear in the record, the testimony of the witnesses you've mentioned, preceding as -- it's from pages 5 to 14 and then comes the statement of the Court.","start":332.744,"stop":351.549,"duration":18.8},{"text":"And I have the --","start":351.549,"stop":352.407,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm confused, Your Honor, you're right.","start":352.407,"stop":353.971,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right?","start":353.971,"stop":354.155,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"It was taken before.","start":354.155,"stop":355.634,"duration":1.48},{"text":"He had discussed the matter when he first -- before he took the statement of the witnesses.","start":355.634,"stop":360.618,"duration":4.98},{"text":"He discussed the plea of guilty and so on and the statement says that.","start":360.618,"stop":365.654,"duration":5.04},{"text":"The -- and then after he took that, he described the details of the crime that he got from the defendant then he makes a statement about the plaintiff being free and voluntary.","start":365.654,"stop":374.725,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I see and then he had the interview then he took the testimony --","start":374.725,"stop":376.826,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's right.","start":376.826,"stop":377.539,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and then he made the statement --","start":377.539,"stop":378.805,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":378.805,"stop":379.023,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- from what occurred at the interview.","start":379.023,"stop":380.734,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":380.734,"stop":381.318,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":381.318,"stop":381.816,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"And then after that (Voice Overlap).","start":381.816,"stop":383.538,"duration":1.72},{"text":"Pardon me, Your Honor.","start":383.538,"stop":384.163,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":384.163,"stop":384.306,"duration":0.14},{"text":"Go on please.","start":384.306,"stop":384.85,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Then after that, he then went in -- got the witnesses and went into the details to determine the degree of the murder and he put another sentence -- statement on the file after he sentenced the man to determine the degree of guilt and it --","start":384.85,"stop":400.645,"duration":15.79}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"It was only as to the --","start":400.645,"stop":402.58,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":402.58,"stop":403.024,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the sentence, wasn't it?","start":403.024,"stop":404.779,"duration":1.75},{"text":"Rather than the -- he has the right to plead guilty.","start":404.779,"stop":408.276,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":408.276,"stop":409.235,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"And then they put on the testimony to show the character of the facts so they might arrive with the sentence, is that right?","start":409.235,"stop":414.884,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":414.884,"stop":415.181,"duration":0.3},{"text":"To determine the degree of guilt, so he can arrive at the sentence.","start":415.181,"stop":417.721,"duration":2.54},{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":417.721,"stop":418.359,"duration":0.64},{"text":"Let's go down incidentally.","start":418.359,"stop":420.108,"duration":1.75},{"text":"But today, the whole proceeding, the discussion between the judge and the defendant is put on record, the proceedings surrounding the plea of guilty and our Court rule provides for that.","start":420.108,"stop":432.58,"duration":12.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But what we have is Ms. Zeedyke exactly -- the witnesses for determining what sentence to impose, that was put on record as you call it being an -- a stenographer took it down --","start":432.58,"stop":447.059,"duration":14.48}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":447.059,"stop":447.209,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and transcribed and it's now on file in the Kalamazoo Court.","start":447.209,"stop":450.124,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor and it was taken the same day that he pleaded guilty.","start":450.124,"stop":454.059,"duration":3.94},{"text":"The Court then put another statement on record regarding the sentence that he had determined that the defendant was guilty of first degree murder after this interview with these witnesses and he say -- he ended up saying he thought he should be sentenced to first degree to life because under our statutory, it's mandatory.","start":454.059,"stop":474.045,"duration":19.99},{"text":"And then, he -- he said there in making that statement --","start":474.045,"stop":478.598,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- abolished the death penalty by that time?","start":478.598,"stop":481.388,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't have -- we never had any death penalty.","start":481.388,"stop":483.121,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You never have hadn't --","start":483.121,"stop":484.203,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"The only death in our State was under a federal statute of a robbery (Inaudible).","start":484.203,"stop":490.037,"duration":5.83},{"text":"That's the only death penalty.","start":490.037,"stop":490.975,"duration":0.94},{"text":"We have never had any in Michigan.","start":490.975,"stop":492.928,"duration":1.95},{"text":"It's not a capital offense.","start":492.928,"stop":494.205,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":494.205,"stop":494.687,"duration":0.48},{"text":"Was there any provision in the law at that time for the appointment of counsel in such cases?","start":494.687,"stop":502.882,"duration":8.19}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Not at that time, Your Honor.","start":502.882,"stop":504.198,"duration":1.32},{"text":"That came under 35-A.","start":504.198,"stop":505.516,"duration":1.32},{"text":"However, the courts did appoint counsel.","start":505.516,"stop":508.632,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Under what?","start":508.632,"stop":508.864,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"There was appointment of counsel, but none in a situation like this in a plea of guilty.","start":508.864,"stop":513.537,"duration":4.67},{"text":"It wasn't required, today it is.","start":513.537,"stop":516.722,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"In every criminal case --","start":516.722,"stop":518.053,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"In every criminal case -- pardon?","start":518.053,"stop":520.336,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"In every felony case?","start":520.336,"stop":521.599,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Even misdemeanor cases under that statute.","start":521.599,"stop":523.672,"duration":2.07},{"text":"I quoted yesterday that we just adopted and that's always been the case.","start":523.672,"stop":527.735,"duration":4.06},{"text":"Any misdemeanor case can have an attorney appointed by the court from the arraignment.","start":527.735,"stop":532.385,"duration":4.65},{"text":"The prelim -- preliminary examination in which it's not a criminal proceeding ipso facto, it then become such until it's bound -- he's bound over the Circuit Court.","start":532.385,"stop":541.491,"duration":9.11},{"text":"But we have gone even further to protect the defendants now and we allow -- allowed that testimony to be -- an attorney be pointed on the examination so from every step, he has an attorney.","start":541.491,"stop":552.404,"duration":10.91}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you have a post conviction proceeding at the time this happened?","start":552.404,"stop":556.919,"duration":4.51}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I was going to point out.","start":556.919,"stop":558.056,"duration":1.14},{"text":"I know Mr. Justice Brennan asked about that yesterday, in regard to a delay in motion for a new trial.","start":558.056,"stop":565.098,"duration":7.04},{"text":"Now, our leading case on that is People against (Inaudible) and that case is 218 Mich and which must be at least 30 years old, but our court -- we haven't got any court rule on it.","start":565.098,"stop":575.845,"duration":10.75},{"text":"Our courts have always used that as part of their inherent power to correct any injustice.","start":575.845,"stop":580.753,"duration":4.91},{"text":"So, it's been in Michigan from the very first as far as I can determine.","start":580.753,"stop":584.118,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean there was an appeal that he could have taken a delayed appeal --","start":584.118,"stop":587.557,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":587.557,"stop":587.769,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- anytime?","start":587.769,"stop":588.638,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"And it's a very informal proceeding.","start":588.638,"stop":590.181,"duration":1.54},{"text":"He files a motion for a delay -- leave to file a delay in motion for a new trial and that he's got to set up his reasoning grounds and justify his delay beyond excuse.","start":590.181,"stop":599.133,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"That was then done by rule of court or --","start":599.133,"stop":601.13,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":601.13,"stop":601.988,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"There is a rule, is there?","start":601.988,"stop":603.404,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":603.404,"stop":604.292,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"There was at that time?","start":604.292,"stop":605.23,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":605.23,"stop":605.668,"duration":0.44},{"text":"There's always been one in Michigan.","start":605.668,"stop":607.233,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":607.233,"stop":607.809,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"And here, Willie Moore did have the opportunity to file such a motion, but he waited almost 12 years before doing so and I say that -- that procedure is very informal, our courts and magistrate (Inaudible).","start":607.809,"stop":620.909,"duration":13.1},{"text":"In fact, we're getting now -- we're -- we're going to pass a statute soon which makes all criminal cases appealable in that State.","start":620.909,"stop":626.44,"duration":5.53},{"text":"We don't have the right now.","start":626.44,"stop":627.657,"duration":1.22},{"text":"You have the right to file an implication to lead to appeal.","start":627.657,"stop":630.42,"duration":2.76},{"text":"But we also have another proceeding and that's a motion for leave to file a delay -- a delayed application for leave to appeal and that can be filed anytime and that's a very informal proceeding.","start":630.42,"stop":642.927,"duration":12.51},{"text":"The record is settled and then the court can -- can open up the whole case and that's what was done here after 12 years and that's why Willie Moore got into our Supreme Court.","start":642.927,"stop":652.049,"duration":9.12},{"text":"Now, I'd like to point out here that after the hearing on this delayed motion for a new trial, our court in Kalamazoo appointed an attorney for him.","start":652.049,"stop":660.163,"duration":8.11},{"text":"They paid -- the County paid -- and they paid for the record in before your Griffin against Illinois case, we furnished the transcript for the defendants here and paid for it.","start":660.163,"stop":667.873,"duration":7.71},{"text":"So, our -- our State has been over backwards, I think, in trying to give Willie Moore due process in this case.","start":667.873,"stop":675.58,"duration":7.71}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"When is the first -- when is the first time it's shown by the record that Willie Moore tried either to get counsel appointed or -- or possible (Inaudible)?","start":675.58,"stop":686.847,"duration":11.27}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I see it here, the first motion he made was September 1949 and he got an attorney of his own choice, Mr. Roxboro who is a very able and experienced attorney.","start":686.847,"stop":700.434,"duration":13.59},{"text":"He's colored and he has handled a great number of these cases and I'd like to say here now that I'm surprised that when they first filed this delayed motion for a new trial, there was nothing said about duress.","start":700.434,"stop":712.917,"duration":12.48},{"text":"The only thing they went upon was the De Meerleer case which he mentioned here yesterday and that was grounded on the failure to appoint counsel, failure to inform him on the consequences of his plea and -- and the fact that he was rushed into a hearing without experience and it was frankly verbatim De Meerleer But after they had the hearing under the delayed motion for a new trial which followed this hearing, part of it, then they Sheriff Struble made a remark about the tension on that that time and then he brought that in and I'd like to refer the Court to where that happened.","start":712.917,"stop":748.41,"duration":35.49},{"text":"On page 9, the grounds of the delayed motion for a new trial are sent out in my brief and they're verbatim from De Meerleer.","start":748.41,"stop":756.081,"duration":7.67},{"text":"And then, on -- on page 23 at the delay hearing on the delayed motion for a new trial, after Sheriff Struble testified, Willie Moore testified, Mr. Roxboro advised the Court as follows.","start":756.081,"stop":774.97,"duration":18.89},{"text":"No, excuse me.","start":774.97,"stop":775.698,"duration":0.73},{"text":"Before he -- before the proceeding started, and Mr. Roxboro informed the court as follows.","start":775.698,"stop":781.354,"duration":5.66},{"text":"“So, there won't be any misunderstandings.","start":781.354,"stop":784.643,"duration":3.29},{"text":"We aren't relying on any general allegation.","start":784.643,"stop":788.421,"duration":3.78},{"text":"We are relying on just two things, on this record and on the De Meerleer case.","start":788.421,"stop":794.362,"duration":5.94},{"text":"I would like to call the court's attention that at the time Willie B. Moore -- and at that time, Willie B. Moore was 17 years of age.”","start":794.362,"stop":801.021,"duration":6.66},{"text":"I don't -- I've better put on my glasses.","start":801.021,"stop":803.161,"duration":2.14},{"text":"The extent of his education then was at seventh-grade education and it is our contention that he did not have a fair trial and that contention is substantiated by the case of De Meerleer versus the People on the State of Michigan and then he quoted -- cites it then.","start":803.161,"stop":819.069,"duration":15.91},{"text":"It is our contention that this case is directly in point and fits on all four the case before the bar at that time and then the assistant prosecutor who was conducting the examination said, so there won't be any mistakes, I want this to be down if that's what they're going on, but then after Rubel (ph) testified and Willie Moore testified, they asked to amend the motion for a new trial to include duress and so on.","start":819.069,"stop":845.716,"duration":26.65},{"text":"The -- and the court allowed them and continued the hearing and they brought in more witnesses and the people brought in more witnesses.","start":845.716,"stop":854.727,"duration":9.01},{"text":"Now, there was something said here about the promise of leniency made by Mr. Chapman.","start":854.727,"stop":859.904,"duration":5.18},{"text":"The record shows that Willie Moore said that Mr. (Inaudible), the prosecutor promised him leniency and that this was okayed by Chapman.","start":859.904,"stop":871.044,"duration":11.14},{"text":"Now, we -- the people weren't able to refute that for this reason.","start":871.044,"stop":876.384,"duration":5.34},{"text":"First of all, Mr. (Inaudible) is paralytic now.","start":876.384,"stop":879.475,"duration":3.09},{"text":"He can't speak and the record shows that.","start":879.475,"stop":883.322,"duration":3.85},{"text":"He's an old man and he's just -- and that -- and that he's suffering from incapacity and Chapman is in Florida and he weren't -- they weren't able to get him and that's why that wasn't refuted.","start":883.322,"stop":895.01,"duration":11.69},{"text":"But anyhow, after that happened, the judge heard all the witnesses, both pro and con and the -- all the testimony regarding the fact that there was duress and so on, appeared to Willie Moore.","start":895.01,"stop":908.161,"duration":13.15},{"text":"The only other testimony regarding the tension in the community came from Sheriff Struble who said that the -- there was a lot of tension at that time and he told them that he pleaded guilty if he were guilty ought to plead guilty, but he said also that he told him that if he weren't guilty, he'd stand firm and protect you.","start":908.161,"stop":927.427,"duration":19.27},{"text":"That's what he said and that's what they're relying on chiefly in his brief.","start":927.427,"stop":930.974,"duration":3.55},{"text":"There are other witnesses who took the stand afterwards.","start":930.974,"stop":933.057,"duration":2.08},{"text":"Who said screw Hummel and two or three other officers took the stand and said there wasn't any tension in the community, it was a usual thing when you got a murder of this kind.","start":933.057,"stop":942.362,"duration":9.3},{"text":"People were talking about it in the record.","start":942.362,"stop":944.518,"duration":2.16},{"text":"There was also -- Willie Moore said that he was worried because people banged on his doors.","start":944.518,"stop":950.842,"duration":6.32},{"text":"He was in a solitary cell.","start":950.842,"stop":952.305,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Solicitor General.","start":952.305,"stop":953.089,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":953.089,"stop":953.883,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Wasn't that also his approval that he testified when they took him to Kalamazoo and some other place and --","start":953.883,"stop":961.591,"duration":7.71}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"-- took him by the (Inaudible) yes.","start":961.591,"stop":962.926,"duration":1.34},{"text":"They took him (Voice Overlap) --","start":962.926,"stop":963.989,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- route or something because of the tension --","start":963.989,"stop":967.144,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":967.144,"stop":967.685,"duration":0.54},{"text":"He did.","start":967.685,"stop":968.522,"duration":0.84},{"text":"You see, they took him to Jackson Prison on the same day.","start":968.522,"stop":971.816,"duration":3.29},{"text":"There are two routes and I got it from this record.","start":971.816,"stop":973.993,"duration":2.18},{"text":"I'm not a Kalamazoo resident, but he said that he heard there was going to be some trouble.","start":973.993,"stop":978.269,"duration":4.28},{"text":"And on a part of a group of colored fellows, they're going to take Willie Moore away and then there was another group of Holland fellows, they were going to interfere, so he said he took the back roads avoiding any trouble.","start":978.269,"stop":988.629,"duration":10.36},{"text":"I think he acted like any good law enforcement officer would in a situation of this kind.","start":988.629,"stop":993.648,"duration":5.02},{"text":"But I say that in regard to the tension that was disputed by other witnesses, the only -- Judge Fox who was the assistant prosecutor at that time that he wasn't aware of any tension.","start":993.648,"stop":1006.39,"duration":12.74},{"text":"I tried to describe to you yesterday the jail that was involved and as you noticed, it is quite a structure.","start":1006.39,"stop":1012.187,"duration":5.8},{"text":"Now, the top of that jail, they went as only up to the fourth floor.","start":1012.187,"stop":1016.862,"duration":4.67},{"text":"The top there shows a cement wall if you look at the appendix.","start":1016.862,"stop":1021.002,"duration":4.14},{"text":"Now, that wall surrounds -- the fifth floor is sort of a penthouse and the jail itself is back from the edge of the building, about four feet and then there are windows for look out.","start":1021.002,"stop":1033.493,"duration":12.49},{"text":"But in further, those windows appeared in this cement wall which goes six or seven feet up above the jail and the jail itself is about 60 feet to 75 feet high.","start":1033.493,"stop":1043.615,"duration":10.12},{"text":"Now, the only entrance to these cells are first, the elevator, which has been described and that's used only for prisoners and it's a very small elevator.","start":1043.615,"stop":1051.27,"duration":7.65},{"text":"I think it's about twice as wide as this stand and it has a lock in the basement and it's unlocked when prisoners are taken into jail by the sheriff.","start":1051.27,"stop":1061.282,"duration":10.01},{"text":"Then, it doesn't stop the first floor.","start":1061.282,"stop":1062.816,"duration":1.53},{"text":"It stops at the second floor where the court is and it stops at the fifth floor where the jail is.","start":1062.816,"stop":1067.677,"duration":4.86},{"text":"I don't think he can get over five or six people in that -- in that elevator.","start":1067.677,"stop":1071.254,"duration":3.58},{"text":"And then, there's a stairway to right of there.","start":1071.254,"stop":1073.43,"duration":2.18},{"text":"It's a very narrow stairway and the door leads into the outer room in the jail where the prisoners are booked.","start":1073.43,"stop":1081.719,"duration":8.29},{"text":"It's a very narrow stairway as I'd say and the door is made up of cement -- of steel.","start":1081.719,"stop":1086.497,"duration":4.78},{"text":"And then, there's another stairway that goes into the part where the judge lived at that time.As the record says, the judge had an apartment in the jail himself and that was up towards the front.","start":1086.497,"stop":1095.982,"duration":9.48},{"text":"Now, that door has a very -- that stairway is also narrow and it has a steel door and it only opens from the inside.","start":1095.982,"stop":1103.09,"duration":7.11},{"text":"It can't be open from the outside and then there's another iron door that blocks off any entrance into the -- the main room here, so you can see the situation at this time.","start":1103.09,"stop":1112.906,"duration":9.82},{"text":"I don't believe Willie Moore, when he says there were people there, they couldn't because there's an outer office, it's a very small one and then there's another steel door that leads into where the cell is which is on the right and that -- and left to that is the kitchen and they had a very cook there and I thought it was a very pleasant (Inaudible) better than some hotel I've been in.","start":1112.906,"stop":1133.096,"duration":20.19}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there any restitution -- was there any reputation of Willie Moore's statement that people have come up there and banged on his door?","start":1133.096,"stop":1141.976,"duration":8.88}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes and Struble and a couple of other said that there were (Voice Overlap) --","start":1141.976,"stop":1145.005,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Struble, who is Struble?","start":1145.005,"stop":1146.168,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"He's the sheriff at that time.","start":1146.168,"stop":1147.382,"duration":1.21},{"text":"Hummel said it and a couple of other people.","start":1147.382,"stop":1150.502,"duration":3.12},{"text":"And incidentally, Struble said that they used to have crowd there but they were church groups (Inaudible)","start":1150.502,"stop":1157.542,"duration":7.04},{"text":"And this cell as I say isn't really solitary, there are two -- two bunks in it and they had a good will drunken at the day I was there and it's used as a federal prison too, so that's the situation.","start":1157.542,"stop":1170.386,"duration":12.84},{"text":"And everything that Willie Moore contended here came out of the hearing that day and he's complaining about that hearing now in saying, “We can't use that reconstructing testimony,” but I don't think that's fair.","start":1170.386,"stop":1182.091,"duration":11.7},{"text":"To use a testimony to support his side of the argument and then try to prevent us from doing -- doing it.","start":1182.091,"stop":1187.749,"duration":5.66},{"text":"I don't know how you remember a famous two-handed archer in mythology.","start":1187.749,"stop":1192.316,"duration":4.57},{"text":"He's going to act on his right hand and if he missed it, he then changed it and shot you with left hand.","start":1192.316,"stop":1196.843,"duration":4.53},{"text":"And I think that's exactly what's happening to us here.","start":1196.843,"stop":1200.447,"duration":3.6},{"text":"Anyhow, I believe that our brief shows that all of these contentions have been denied.","start":1200.447,"stop":1206.166,"duration":5.72},{"text":"Three courts have passed on it, the trial court before whom appears, he appeared to have a chance to observe misdemeanor and he came into conclusion, no compulsion were used.","start":1206.166,"stop":1216.954,"duration":10.79},{"text":"Then, he had the judge on the hearing on the motion for a new trial and he said he didn't believe Willie Moore.","start":1216.954,"stop":1222.536,"duration":5.58}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1222.536,"stop":1224.129,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I didn't know (Inaudible)","start":1224.129,"stop":1229.931,"duration":5.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1229.931,"stop":1232.32,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel J. Torina","textObjs":[{"text":"The 1948 and he died just after the Quicksall case which he passed on.","start":1232.32,"stop":1237.345,"duration":5.03},{"text":"He was the same judge incidentally in that case.","start":1237.345,"stop":1239.789,"duration":2.44},{"text":"What I know of, I mean he's a very kind gentleman and was most meticulous in his cases.","start":1239.789,"stop":1243.698,"duration":3.91},{"text":"His statement not stereotype.","start":1243.698,"stop":1245.292,"duration":1.59},{"text":"It goes into details and then after Judge Sweet passed on it, our Supreme Court passed on it and they decided it on the question of facts, the credibility of Willie Moore and I think that is the whole issue here.","start":1245.292,"stop":1256.953,"duration":11.66},{"text":"Whom are you going to believe, Willie Moore now after waiting all this time?","start":1256.953,"stop":1261.274,"duration":4.32},{"text":"Or you're going to believe the Court which had a chance to observe misdemeanor?","start":1261.274,"stop":1264.626,"duration":3.35},{"text":"I think under the facts and circumstances in this case, our State has done everything possible to provide due process for Willie Moore and the judgment should be affirmed.","start":1264.626,"stop":1273.778,"duration":9.15},{"text":"I think the Court -- if there are any questions, I'd be glad to answer them but I'd appreciate your attention and your time.","start":1273.778,"stop":1279.415,"duration":5.64}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":1279.415,"stop":1281.078,"duration":1.66},{"text":"Mr. Culver, do you -- yes.","start":1281.078,"stop":1285.423,"duration":4.35},{"text":"You have a little time left.","start":1285.423,"stop":1286.51,"duration":1.09},{"text":"You may proceed.","start":1286.51,"stop":1287.561,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please.","start":1287.561,"stop":1288.405,"duration":0.84},{"text":"First of all, I would like to indicate to the Court that clearly the issue of duress and the arrest and coercion is in this case.","start":1288.405,"stop":1299.365,"duration":10.96},{"text":"The record shows that the Court granted a motion of attorney Roxboro to bring that into the case and that secondly, I wish to point out to the Court that although at one time, this was based on the De Meerleer case in the initial part of the proceeding that subsequently after Mr. Roxboro heard the testimony and after he got into -- into the proceeding that it was extended and we would ask as I've indicated when we started out, the attempt is to put this into a category with, we'll say De Meerleer and Quicksall or something like that.","start":1299.365,"stop":1333.507,"duration":34.14},{"text":"This case is the case as they all are seems to me onto themselves.","start":1333.507,"stop":1338.335,"duration":4.83},{"text":"And then finally, I would like to answer Mr. Justice Frankfurter's question which I think he recently asked and which I think raises the distinct problem here and that is, how do you get around the fact that the trial judge, Judge Weimer said, “I'm satisfied that this is freely and voluntary made”.","start":1338.335,"stop":1354.83,"duration":16.49},{"text":"And I -- I submit the answer to that is that no one, not even Mr. Moore's lawyers knew until 1951 of the fact that Sheriff Struble had been afraid and had warned Mr. Moore that if he -- if that -- he was afraid that he couldn't protect you.","start":1354.83,"stop":1376.847,"duration":22.02},{"text":"And therefore, that even though the statement by Judge Weimer was contemporaneous with the -- with the sentence that I submit that Judge Weimer himself didn't know what we know right now and that was that the sheriff has told his men that he couldn't protect him.","start":1376.847,"stop":1392.151,"duration":15.3},{"text":"Now, he knew all the rest of the things.","start":1392.151,"stop":1393.612,"duration":1.46},{"text":"He knew about the youth and inexperienced Mr. Moore but he didn't know the facts that we know now.","start":1393.612,"stop":1399.861,"duration":6.25},{"text":"And therefore, I submit to you that we -- we wish to depend upon this delayed -- this right of a delayed motion and the right to this testimony in the record because it does show something that is going -- that's why we'll show up again before this Court and that is that the sentencing judge on a plea of guilty may not know all of the circumstances and it can only be dug out by an attorney and by cross examination.","start":1399.861,"stop":1423.86,"duration":24},{"text":"And another thing I'd like to point out is that after Mr. Struble, the sheriff was put on in testifying in this case that the prosecution then spend a day and a half trying to -- to prejudice trying to show that Mr. Sheriff Struble was wrong and of course you've got the pictures of the jail and everything that shows that this man couldn't possibly has been subject to duress.","start":1423.86,"stop":1449.191,"duration":25.33},{"text":"But you'll notice that nobody -- that -- that he wasn't in that jail all the time that he was only there one night according to Sheriff Struble and nobody agrees about that and I submit that it's outside the record, but the man was kept in the police headquarters in a jail in the basement or if you want to get down there, you just walk down the stairs.","start":1449.191,"stop":1466.692,"duration":17.5},{"text":"You don't have to go pass an officer at all.","start":1466.692,"stop":1469.224,"duration":2.53},{"text":"So, I submit to the Court again that the issue of duress and coercion is before the Court and it's in the -- in the record.","start":1469.224,"stop":1477.683,"duration":8.46},{"text":"And secondly, that he didn't -- we don't pretend that this is the De Meerleer case.We think it looks a little like the De Meerleer case.","start":1477.683,"stop":1485.671,"duration":7.99},{"text":"It looks a little like the Quicksall case, but that's -- that the -- our only hope of success, I submitted the fact that this Court is the last word and that this will be a People versus Moore case which you don't try that to correlate and say, “Well, it doesn't fit in any case that's been before the Court exactly.”","start":1485.671,"stop":1504.137,"duration":18.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Culver, before you sit down.","start":1504.137,"stop":1507.672,"duration":3.54},{"text":"What lead you to say that the sheriff told Willie Moore that he couldn't (Inaudible) I thought I read in the (Inaudible) just the opposite?","start":1507.672,"stop":1518.326,"duration":10.65}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think if the Court please that in reading page 52 and 53 -- in 52 he says, I told him if he was guilty, he might better own up --","start":1518.326,"stop":1527.495,"duration":9.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But before that.","start":1527.495,"stop":1528.983,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that?","start":1528.983,"stop":1529.752,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you tell Willie Moore that he couldn't protect him or words with that effect (Inaudible).","start":1529.752,"stop":1535.534,"duration":5.78},{"text":"You didn't tell him that?","start":1535.534,"stop":1536.518,"duration":0.98},{"text":"No.","start":1536.518,"stop":1537.092,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1537.092,"stop":1537.974,"duration":0.88},{"text":"But then he contended and he says, “It is my duty and it's up to me to protect you, to use every effort at my command to protect you.","start":1537.974,"stop":1545.02,"duration":7.05},{"text":"But I said the tension is high out there and I'm just telling you what could happen if it was started by someone else.","start":1545.02,"stop":1551.736,"duration":6.72},{"text":"I don't know what language I used in the end.","start":1551.736,"stop":1555.533,"duration":3.8},{"text":"Regardless, that was substantially what he said.","start":1555.533,"stop":1558.324,"duration":2.79},{"text":"Now, we know the reaction of that statement, I mean, if he said it to you, I wouldn't -- certainly, wouldn't have frightened you probably.","start":1558.324,"stop":1565.45,"duration":7.13},{"text":"But he said it to this Willie Moore and Willie Moore has testified and I think it's uncontradictive that after the man told me he couldn't protect me, otherwise that's what Willie Moore --","start":1565.45,"stop":1576.375,"duration":10.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That was Willie Moore said 11 years later --","start":1576.375,"stop":1578.352,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1578.352,"stop":1578.843,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that what he thinks the sheriff said, nothing is more to him than people asking why -- beginning to think things we've said and weren't said.","start":1578.843,"stop":1586.822,"duration":7.98}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"That's --","start":1586.822,"stop":1586.893,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the most common plaything in -- on the part of a perfectly honest people.","start":1586.893,"stop":1591.307,"duration":4.41}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1591.307,"stop":1592.502,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Why didn't you bring that out (Inaudible).","start":1592.502,"stop":1596.278,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"In 1948 or 1949?","start":1596.278,"stop":1597.972,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1597.972,"stop":1600.857,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe, if the Court please, because it appears that his attorney at that time was not too well versed in the fact of the matter.","start":1600.857,"stop":1610.551,"duration":9.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1610.551,"stop":1612.347,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Culver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1612.347,"stop":1613.295,"duration":0.95},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1613.295,"stop":1617.053,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Culver, I -- I know the Court would have me say to you that you're appreciated of the great time and effort that you have put in without compensation for this penniless prisoner and regardless of the way your case might turn out, you've rendered a real service to the public and used them as a credit to the bar.","start":1617.053,"stop":1640.476,"duration":23.42},{"text":"And Mr. Solicitor General, we appreciate your frankness and your zeal in defending the laws in the institution of your statement.","start":1640.476,"stop":1648.371,"duration":7.89}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1648.371,"stop":1654.531,"duration":6.16}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Oct  15 - 16, 1957","petitioner":"Moore","respondent":"Michigan","docket":"42","citation":"355 US 155 (1957)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/355/155","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Dec 9, 1957"}